            <div type="glosses" subtype="textual">
                <note xml:id="LILLEMETAMARK" resp="#DCH"><p><hi rend="bold">Insertion symbol (MS IA, <hi rend="italic">g</hi>.1)&#x2014;</hi>The symbol directs the reader to move and insert above line 99 
                    (&#x201C;Colossal form and figure fair&#x201D;) the couplet forming lines 105&#x2013;6, which is bracketed in the manuscript (&#x201C;Those ancient piles rose large and high / In rich irregularity&#x201D;); 
                    see <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="editorial_rationale_note.php#METAMARKS">Editorial and Encoding Rationale and Methodology: Element, Attribute, and Value Usage&#x2014;Metamarks</ref>. 
                    The lines appear in their revised order in the <title type="manuscript" corresp="#MSIX">MS IX</title> version of the poem, and the order continues as such through 
                    <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="poems_1891_note.php#JRPOEMS1891"><hi rend="italic"><title type="book" corresp="#JRPOEMS1891">Poems</title></hi> (1891)</ref> and the 
                    <ref type="note" subtype="bibliographical" target="library_edition_note.php#JRWORKSLE"><title type="book" corresp="#JRWORKSLE">Library Edition</title> (1903)</ref>.</p>
                </note>
                
                <note xml:id="LILLEDRAWINGSPACE" resp="#DCH"><p><hi rend="bold">Space for drawing (MS IX)&#x2014;</hi>At the bottom of the page (18r), five lines of space following the end of the poem 
                    could have accommodated a small drawing, if a figure was intended, or if one was produced but lost.</p></note>
                
